Crimea and Sudetenland, same battle?
BRUSSELS – The annexation of Crimea by Russia constitutes the gravest example of aggression in peacetime that Europe has witnessed since the annexation of the Sudetenland by Nazi Germany in 1938.
It is certainly today's practice to downplay the importance of the "lessons of Munich" when discussing this episode in which Neville Chamberlain and Édouard Daladier yielded to Hitler's demands regarding Czechoslovakia in an attempt to appease the Führer.
However, if the Western world were to turn a blind eye to the annexation of Crimea – the second case of a sovereign territory being invaded by Russian President Vladimir Putin, after the takeover of the Georgian regions of Abkhazia and South Ossetia in 2008 – current democratic leaders might bitterly regret their inaction.
In Western capitals, reactions so far have been mixed.
The currently considered sanctions – such as expulsion from the G8, for instance – might seem amusing if the threat to peace in Europe were not so serious.
Putin considers the collapse of the Soviet Union to be the gravest catastrophe of modern times, the man striving without rest to resurrect a fallen Russian empire.
If the West is to be taken seriously, it will need to act with the same determination that Putin demonstrates.
The numerous successes of the Russian president within the framework of his imperial project have thus far cost him virtually nothing.
His initiative for an Eurasian Economic Community has brought a number of resource-rich states, such as Kazakhstan, Uzbekistan, and Turkmenistan, into Russia's fold.
Georgia was divided in 2008.
As for the Armenian government, Russian intimidation led it to reject the association agreement proposed by the European Union.
And here lies the most precious geostrategic prize of all – Ukraine – potentially falling into Putin's hands.
Without Ukraine, Russia "ceases to be an empire," as explained by the former US national security advisor Zbigniew Brzezinski; "on the other hand, with a subverted and subordinate Ukraine, Russia automatically becomes an empire again." And since the overwhelming majority of Ukrainians do not aspire to join Putin's empire, it is highly likely that the country led by Russian President Putin is now a highly militarized state, akin to a Soviet Union without a Communist Party.
