Cancellations of summits, proposals for trade agreements, and other participation in forums as ineffective as the G8 will not suffice.
Only actions involving the imposition of tangible economic sanctions, which could affect Russian citizens – who, let us recall, continue to re-elect Putin to power – can give us hope that the Kremlin will leave its expansionary path.
Of what sanctions could we be speaking?
First, Turkey could decide to close the Dardanelles Strait to Russian shipments, as it did after the Russo-Georgian war in 2008.
At the time, Turkey had blocked access to the Black Sea to prevent the United States from intervening, although it now appears clearly that this was not the intention of the United States.
Today, Turkey could choose to close the Turkish Straits not only to Russian warships but also to all commercial vessels heading to Russian ports in the Black Sea.
The impact on Russia's economy – as well as on Putin's military aspirations – would be significant.
Turkey is authorized to close the Dardanelles under an amendment added in 1982 to the 1936 Montreux Convention.
Turkey could thus turn against Putin the very argument he invoked to justify the annexation of Crimea – namely, that he was protecting Russian ethnicities there – by asserting that it is itself protecting its Turkish cousins of Tatar origin, who, given the mistreatment they have suffered at the hands of Russia, clearly wish to remain under Ukrainian rule.
This week, Turkish Foreign Minister Ahmet Davutoğlu ordered his plane to turn back mid-air to head to Kiev to support the new interim government.
The Prime Minister Recep Tayyip Erdoğan, who is no soft touch like Putin knows, could thus follow suit by immediately closing the Turkish Straits to Russian shipments – until Putin withdraws all his troops from Crimea back to their bases, namely those in Sevastopol or Russia.
It would be good for Turkey to rely on the guarantee provided by Article 5 of the NATO treaty should Russia seek to intimidate it.
Second, President Barack Obama could impose the same type of financial sanctions on Russia that he imposed on Iran regarding its nuclear program.
These sanctions have indeed significantly undermined the Iranian economy.
Similarly, refusing access to the American financial system for all banks dealing with Russian banks or companies would generate unprecedented economic chaos in Russia since the fall of communism.
The Russian citizens must understand that allowing Putin – whose rise to power is based on his promise to end the shortages of the early post-Soviet era – to continue his aggressive imperialist path could come at a great cost to them.
Thirdly, it would be possible for Obama to remind the Chinese of their role in Eurasian stability.
A Putin, the disintegration of the Soviet Union constituted the most formidable geostrategic windfall one can imagine.
In an instant, this empire, which had seized millions of hectares of Chinese territory over the centuries and threatened the People's Republic with nuclear annihilation, simply vanished.
Since then, the independent Central Asian states, and Ukraine itself, have become important trading partners of China.
The invasion of Georgia by Russia seriously displeased China, as was evident at the Shanghai Cooperation Organization summit held after the war (this regional grouping bringing together a number of former Soviet states bordering both China and the motherland).
Russia tried to get the SCO to recognize the independence of Abkhazia and South Ossetia.
The organization, however, expressed its disagreement.
Or, the Central Asian member countries – Kazakhstan, Kyrgyzstan, Tajikistan, and Uzbekistan – would never have been able to stand up to the Kremlin without China’s support.
It now falls to Chinese President Xi Jinping to be less enigmatic in his response to Putin's provocations.
The true test of this Chinese claim to be a genuine and responsible actor within the international community will play out very soon at the United Nations.
Will China support this clear violation of international law committed by Putin, or will it stand in support of Ukraine's territorial integrity?
Two other avenues for sanctions are also conceivable.
Each Russian leader could thus have their visas refused or revoked.
It would also be possible to freeze a number of assets, including those that have been laundered by Putin's close oligarchs.
It is only when the pain becomes unbearable, especially for the elites, that this kind of struggle that Putin is waging today will fail.
The price of inaction could well prove considerable.
Many countries, from Japan to Israel, rely on America's promise to act firmly against any serious threat to peace.
Moreover, when Ukraine renounced its nuclear arsenal in 1994, it did so on the express condition that the United States (alongside the United Kingdom, France, and Russia) guaranteed its territorial integrity.
If Crimea were to remain annexed, no one can blame Ukraine if it decides to renuclearize its defense (something it remains technologically capable of doing).
When Chamberlain returned from Munich, Winston Churchill addressed him with the famous formula: "You had the choice between war and dishonor."
"You chose dishonor, and you will have war." Obama and other Western leaders are now faced with a similar choice.
If they were to make the choice of dishonor, we can be certain that the bold Poutine will eventually serve them another war.
